We all recognize that this is not theory. That doesnt mean the governor of Georgia and @jimcramer is right in their conclusions. But what I tried to respond with was (1) the media has taken the protests out of proportion (as they always do) and (2) the majority of Americans are

not in favor of an early reentry as Kemp and Jim are. The ugly images beamed into our homes trick us into over-weighting the prevalence of the phenomenon—the so-called “availability bias” identified by Nobel Prize winner Daniel Kahneman.

The “availability bias” is a mental shortcut that helps us interpret the prevalence and significance of events. In many situations, the bias works well, but in a world where cable news is dependent on dramatic video, it causes us to misinterpret the true magnitude of events.

There is such rancor and strong opinions on stocks, market strategy, how to deal with Covid-19, etc. All personalize these subjects - rarely allowing for alternative viewpoints. I express my views @revshark hopefully in a data driven manner. Am I biased, of course I am.

Everyone is! But I try to be logical and respectful in my analysis leading to my conclusions. And, though in disagreement, I accept views other than my own. As to politics we will have the November elections soon enough for everyone to vote on their own book!

Though I and others that you comment upon may be sitting at home and working - we all have dear friends and family that suffering severely from the stay at home edicts, Rev. @revshark We are a sympathetic species that can see beyond our own fate... Respectfully.

@carlquintanilla @jimcramer As to your comments about Georgia, in particular... Respectfully: On Monday, a handful of Republican governors decided to gamble with the lives of their citizens and, by extension, with the lives of all Americans.

Governor Brian Kemp announced that Georgia would open movie theaters as early as Friday of this week. I would say that Kemp is an idiot, but that description is way too kind and mean to idiots. Kemp is acting with reckless contempt for the health and safety of Georgians.

Sadly, some Georgians will accept his invitation to gather in public places to make a political statement that “Georgia is not New York.” So stipulated. You don’t need to put your lives in danger to make a point that is obvious from every map of the United States.

While Kemp claims that he will require theaters to impose “social distancing,” he ignores the fact that patrons will touch common surfaces such as seats, snack bars, bathrooms, door handles, walls, trash receptacles, elevator buttons, ticket machines, and ATMs. Need I go on?
No? But I will. Kemp will also allow Georgians to receive haircuts, pedicures, massages, and tattoos—all while maintaining social distancing. Sure, if you say so, Brian!

It is an unfortunate truth that Americans have become conditioned to think in fifteen-minute increments—the average length of time between “breaking news alerts” on our smartphones. National crises are expected to resolve within a week. If a crisis lasts longer than that,

@jicramer @carlquintanilla I respectfully disagree with your statements on Georgia... The first step in maintaining perspective is to acknowledge the unavoidable amplification generated by media coverage. While Trump sent a clarion call to his supporters, only a few hundred

showed up around the nation. On a percentage basis, their numbers are effectively equal to zero. The ugly images beamed into our homes trick us into over-weighting the prevalence of the phenomenon—the so-called “availability bias” identified by Nobel Prize winner Daniel Kahneman

The “availability bias” is a mental shortcut that helps us interpret the prevalence and significance of events. In many situations, the bias works well, but in a world where cable news is dependent on dramatic video, it causes us to misinterpret the true magnitude of events.

Let’s do the math to see what the small protests in Michigan tell us. Michigan has a population of ten million people. At most, a couple of hundred protestors showed up at the state capitol. What you did not see on your television was 9,999,800 citizens of Michigan peacefully
remaining at home—as Governor Witmer requested. A rational comparison based on the numbers tells us that the protests were insignificant—despite breathless commentators and frightening pictures.

To be fair, there are undoubtedly many people in Michigan who sympathize with the protestors. Okay, let’s look at that. As noted above in the Politico article, most Americans are much more worried about easing restrictions too early than they are about the effect on the economy.

Per the poll, about 47% of Republicans in Michigan are more concerned about the economy than the pandemic. Per a recent PEW Research study, only 34% of Michigan voters are Republican. Even if all 47% of Republicans in Michigan who are worried about the economy want to “liberate”

their state—a doubtful proposition—that would mean that only 16% of Michigan voters support Trump’s call to resist social distancing measures (0.47 X 0.34 = 0.16). Apologies for the math, but it is important that we place Trump’s threats in perspective. For comparison, 29% of

Americans believe in Bigfoot, so if only 16% of voters in Michigan are motivated by Trump’s tweets to “liberate” Michigan, they represent the unavoidable tail in any distribution curve that represents the outliers. In trying to put Trump’s irresponsible tweets in perspective, I

do not mean to minimize the very real economic duress and social discontent that are broadly felt by Americans of every political party. But no one should fear that such discontent can be converted into armed resistance by Trump’s tweets.

to examine the facts objectively and hold them top of mind long after the daily news cycle has faded. We are in for a lengthy fight. I do not make that point to depress you, but rather, to suggest that maintaining a healthy dedication to reality will place us in a stronger

position to deal with the inevitable ebb-and-flow of the pandemic. We may be in for a respite in some places in the nation. Good. We deserve it. But do not confuse that pause for the end of the fight. We must maintain vigilance until a vaccine is developed and 90% of Americans

I hope that the prediction of Dr. Marc Lipsitch is wrong, but it is a near certainty that Governor Kemp’s relaxation of social distancing will result in the deaths of many Georgians—and other Americans. Remember the debacle in Wisconsin’s primary? There is tentative evidence

that Wisconsin GOP’s insistence on holding an in-person primary caused an uptick in infections—although the data is not conclusive. See Talking Points Memo, Did The Wisconsin Primary Spark New Infections? (“There is a jump starting on the 7th day after the election.”) Trump’s

daily briefings have broken new ground in absurdity. He has dropped any pretense that he is attending the briefings to provide information to Americans about the most serious challenge in decades. Instead, he uses the briefings to settle political scores, berate the press,

and lie about his incompetence. On Monday, he spent much of his time criticizing the governors for demanding that the federal government help provide testing resources. In typical Trump fashion he took every conceivable position on testing in a rambling thirty-second statement:

"Not everybody believes we should do so much testing (WTF???). You don’t need so much. We’re talking about maximum, maximum. The reason that the Democrats and some others, maybe, because they don’t know, they want maximum because they want to be able to criticize, because it’s

impossible to get to the maximum number, and yet we’ve been able to do it already. " Despite his incomprehensible bluster, Trump’s efforts are ineffectual. Trump is reaching a small and shrinking hard-core base, while repelling others. See RawStory, “Maryland anti-stay-at-home

protest flops hard as only three people show up.” See also, Vox, “America doesn’t want another Tea Party.” As Vox notes, "Last week, 81 percent of Americans told pollsters for a Politico/Morning Consult poll that the country “should continue to social distance for as long as

is needed to curb the spread of coronavirus, even if it means continued damage to the economy.” Let me repeat that: 81 percent of Americans agree. That’s an astounding figure." Meanwhile, Joe Biden had his best fundraising month ever. See Bloomberg, “Biden Has His Best Monthly
